<para>In C++, ADLX provides smart pointer definitions for the <bold>IADLXInterface</bold> and for all the interfaces that inherit from it. Smart pointers are named identically to their base interface and add the <bold>Ptr</bold> suffix. Example: The smart pointer of <bold>IADLXInterface</bold> is named <bold>IADLXInterfacePtr</bold>.<linebreak/>
</para>
<para>Smart pointers remove the need to call the methods of <bold>IADLXInterface</bold> (<ref refid="_d_o_x__i_a_d_l_x_interface__acquire" kindref="compound">Acquire</ref>, <ref refid="_d_o_x__i_a_d_l_x_interface__release" kindref="compound">Release</ref>, and <ref refid="_d_o_x__i_a_d_l_x_interface__query_interface" kindref="compound">QueryInterface</ref>), as they provide automatic reference counting in the constructor and destructor.<linebreak/>
</para>
<para>For C++, the use of smart pointers is highly recommended and encouraged because they reduce the incidence of memory and resource leaks while maintaining coding efficiency.</para>
